Implementation: Define a Performance Metric¶

It is difficult to measure the quality of a given model without quantifying its performance over training and testing. This is typically done using some type of performance metric
column2: whether it is through calculating some type of error
column4: or some other useful measurement. For this project
column5: you will be calculating the coefficient of determination
column7: to quantify your model's performance. The coefficient of determination for a model is a useful statistic in regression analysis
column8: as it often describes how "good" that model is at making predictions.

column1: The values for R2 range from 0 to 1
column2: which captures the percentage of squared correlation between the predicted and actual values of the target variable. A model with an R2 of 0 is no better than a model that always predicts the mean of the target variable
column3: whereas a model with an R<sup>2</sup> of 1 perfectly predicts the target variable. Any value between 0 and 1 indicates what percentage of the target variable
column5: can be explained by the features. A model can be given a negative R2 as well
column6: which indicates that the model is arbitrarily worse than one that always predicts the mean of the target variable.

Question 7 - Grid Search¶

What is the grid search technique and how it can be applied to optimize a learning algorithm?

Answer: The grid search technique tests ranges of multiple tuning parameters to identify which combination provides the best performance. It does this by exhaustively generating candidates from within a specified grid of parameters
column2: and evalulating each possible combination in turn.

Question 8 - Cross-Validation¶

What is the k-fold cross-validation training technique? What benefit does this technique provide for grid search when optimizing a model?
Hint: Much like the reasoning behind having a testing set
column2: what could go wrong with using grid search without a cross-validated set?

column1: Answer: k-fold cross validation is a technique in which a dataset is divided into k segments
column2: each of which is used as the testing set in one of k independent training experiments (using the other segments as training data); at the completion of all k rounds of training
column3: the results all rounds are averaged to provide the final result.  When using a grid search without a cross validated set
column6: all examples of one type of event will end up in the training data set
column7: while all examples of another event will end up in the test set. The result would be a model that doesn't know anything anything about the event that composes all or most of its testing data
